rn precise file/section-level findings and note any naming or compatibility conflicts you see."}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use"},"type":"assistant","uuid":"82469001-31c6-4856-9466-0588008da443","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:47:33.970Z","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
{"parentUuid":"82469001-31c6-4856-9466-0588008da443","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a89b1e9e76596c6d2","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_57Df3F6lS2kLu95xxRflBiNc","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The following code sections were retrieved:\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improve-pipeline-analysis.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomponent: pipeline-analysis\n     3\tdeliverable: D-0026\n     4\tsource_comparison: comparison-pipeline-analysis.md\n     5\tverdict: IC stronger\n     6\tprinciple_primary: Deterministic Gates\n     7\tprinciple_secondary: Restartability\n     8\tgenerated: 2026-03-15\n     9\t---\n    10\t\n    11\t# Improvement Plan: Pipeline Analysis Subsystem\n    12\t\n    13\tTraceability source: D-0022 merged-strategy.md. All items trace to one or more of the five architectural principles.\n    14\t\n    15\t---\n    16\t\n    17\t## ITEM PA-001 — Pre-Packaged Artifact Collection Before Diagnostic Runs\n...\n    30\t\n    31\t**Dependencies**: None\n    32\t**Acceptance criteria**: `collect_diagnostic_artifacts()` function exists in diagnostic_chain.py; `DiagnosticArtifactBundle` dataclass exists; `run_diagnostic_chain()` calls collection before analysis; analysis stages operate on bundle fields, not on live file reads.\n    33\t**Risk**: Medium. Refactoring diagnostic chain; requires that the bundle covers all artifact types currently read during analysis. Risk of missing an artifact type during collection.\n    34\t\n    35\t---\n    36\t\n    37\t## ITEM PA-002 — Framework-vs-Project Diagnostic Distinction in Output\n...\n    44\t\n    45\t**File paths and change description**:\n    46\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/diagnostic_chain.py` — Add `failure_source: Literal[\"framework\", \"project\", \"unknown\"]` field to `DiagnosticReport`. The classification logic: if the failing gate is for a task specification (`.md` input file) → `\"project\"`; if the failing gate is for a pipeline step (Python code execution) → `\"framework\"`; if ambiguous → `\"unknown\"`.\n    47\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/diagnostic_chain.py` — In the summary stage (stage 4), include the `failure_source` prominently: \"FRAMEWORK ISSUE: The sprint CLI encountered an internal error. Check IC pipeline code.\" vs \"PROJECT ISSUE: The task specification caused the failure. Check tasklist input.\"\n    48\t\n    49\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 5 (Scalable Quality Enforcement), direction 7: \"IC's diagnostic output should distinguish between sprint CLI failures (framework issues) and task specification failures (project issues).\"\n    50\t\n    51\t**Dependencies**: PA-001 (pre-packaged artifacts include the gate output context needed to classify framework vs. project)\n    52\t**Acceptance criteria**: `DiagnosticReport` has `failure_source` field with three allowed values; stage 4 summary includes the failure_source prominently; test verifying that a .md input failure is classified as \"project\" and a pipeline step exception is classified as \"framework.\"\n    53\t**Risk**: Low. Additive field; classification logic is deterministic based on input type.\n    54\t\n    55\t---\n    56\t\n    57\t## ITEM PA-003 — 4-Category Failure Classification in DiagnosticReport\n    58\t\n    59\t**Priority**: P1\n    60\t**Effort**: S\n    61\t**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    62\t**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's 4-category failure taxonomy (execution, template, evidence, workflow failures) as a structured output field in IC's DiagnosticReport, not LW's point-based scoring system\n    63\t**Why not full import**: LW's failure classification uses a point-based confidence scoring system (High ≥5 pts, Medium 3-4, Low ≤2) tied to its batch execution model; IC needs only the four-category labels plus the confidence level concept as a simplified tier (High/Medium/Low based on evidence count, not point arithmetic).\n    64\t\n    65\t**File paths and change description**:\n    66\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/diagnostic_chain.py` — Add `FailureCategory` enum: `EXECUTION_FAILURE`, `TEMPLATE_FAILURE`, `EVIDENCE_FAILURE`, `WORKFLOW_FAILURE`. Add `failure_categories: list[tuple[FailureCategory, ConfidenceLevel]]` to `DiagnosticReport` where `ConfidenceLevel` is `HIGH | MEDIUM | LOW`.\n    67\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/diagnostic_chain.py` — In the analysis stages, classify each identified failure into one of the four categories. `EXECUTION_FAILURE`: model refused, output truncated, timeout. `TEMPLATE_FAILURE`: output does not match expected gate schema. `EVIDENCE_FAILURE`: missing file:line citations, CEV violations. `WORKFLOW_FAILURE`: stage skipped, gate evaluation bypassed.\n    68\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/models.py` — Add `FailureCategory` and `ConfidenceLevel` enums to models module.\n    69\t\n    70\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 5 (Scalable Quality Enforcement), direction 4: \"IC's current diagnostic chain produces free-text analysis without a structured classification. Adopting this taxonomy allows IC to produce scored, categorized failure reports that are actionable and comparable across runs.\"\n    71\t\n    72\t**Dependencies**: PA-001 (artifact bundle provides the evidence to classify failures), PA-002 (framework/project distinction is a prerequisite context for accurate category assignment)\n    73\t**Acceptance criteria**: `FailureCategory` and `ConfidenceLevel` enums exist in models.py; `DiagnosticReport` has `failure_categories` field; each failure identified by the diagnostic chain is categorized; test verifying at least two category types are distinguishable.\n    74\t**Risk**: Medium. Requires that the existing free-text analysis stages are augmented with structured classification logic; staged rollout acceptable (uncategorized failures emit WORKFLOW_FAILURE as fallback).\n    75\t\n    76\t---\n    77\t\n    78\t## ITEM PA-004 — Hard Resource Caps for Recursive Pipeline Analysis\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/strategy-ic-pipeline-analysis.md\n...\n    38\t  - FMEA classifier: `classify_failure_modes()` uses dual-signal detection — Signal 1 (invariant cross-reference: violation without error = silent corruption) + Signal 2 (no-error-path detection: degenerate input categories: EMPTY, NULL, ZERO, NEGATIVE, FILTER_ALL) (`src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/fmea_classifier.py:129`)\n    39\t- **M3 Guard analysis**: `run_guard_analysis_pass()` — detects `if/else` guards, type transitions, cross-references with invariant predicates, checks FMEA severity for elevation to silent corruption (`src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/guard_pass.py:50`)\n    40\t- **M4 Dataflow tracing**: `run_dataflow_tracing_pass()` — builds cross-deliverable state variable graph (birth/write/read nodes), extracts implicit contracts (`ImplicitContract`), detects conflicts\n...\n    51\t\n    52\t**FMEA promotion**: `promote_failure_modes()` (`src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/fmea_promotion.py`) elevates FMEA failure modes to `ReleaseGateViolation` objects when severity exceeds a threshold. These violations propagate to gate criteria as structured reasons for HALT.\n    53\t\n    54\t**Trade-off**: The analytical passes operate on deliverable descriptions (text) rather than actual code. This means the FMEA and invariant analysis is based on what deliverables are _described_ to do, not what they actually implement. A deliverable description that omits a state variable or error condition will not be detected by the analysis passes, creating blind spots for poorly-specified deliverables.\n    55\t\n    56\t## 4. Error Handling Strategy\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improve-adversarial-pipeline.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomponent: adversarial-pipeline\n     3\tdeliverable: D-0026\n     4\tsource_comparison: comparison-adversarial-pipeline.md\n     5\tverdict: IC stronger\n     6\tprinciple_primary: Scalable Quality Enforcement\n     7\tprinciple_secondary: Evidence Integrity\n     8\tgenerated: 2026-03-15\n     9\t---\n    10\t\n    11\t# Improvement Plan: Adversarial Pipeline\n    12\t\n    13\tTraceability source: D-0022 merged-strategy.md. All items trace to one or more of the five architectural principles.\n    14\t\n    15\t---\n    16\t\n    17\t## ITEM AP-001 — Ambient Sycophancy Detection in Agent Definitions\n...\n    24\t\n    25\t**File paths and change description**:\n    26\t- `.claude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Add a \"Sycophancy Detection NFR\" section with: the 12-category taxonomy (immediate agreement, validation seeking, context abandonment, etc.) and the non-linear multiplier rule (1.0× for 1 pattern, 1.3× for 2 patterns, 1.5× for 3+ patterns). Add the four-tier response routing: score < 1.0 → standard response; 1.0–1.3 → explicitly present trade-offs; 1.3–1.5 → escalate to adversarial check; > 1.5 → challenge the premise.\n    27\t- `src/superclaude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Sync copy.\n    28\t- `.claude/agents/self-review.md` — Add the same Sycophancy Detection NFR section (self-review agent is the most susceptible to sycophantic affirmations of the implementer's own work).\n...\n    67\t\n    68\t**File paths and change description**:\n    69\t- `.claude/skills/sc-adversarial-protocol/refs/scoring-protocol.md` — Add a \"Failure Mode Classification\" section with the four categories: (1) Execution failures (model refused, output truncated, agent timeout), (2) Template failures (output does not match artifact schema), (3) Evidence failures (claims without file:line citations, CEV violations), (4) Workflow failures (pipeline stage skipped, convergence plateau not detected). When a debate round produces an artifact with failures, classify each failure before scoring.\n    70\t- `src/superclaude/skills/sc-adversarial-protocol/refs/scoring-protocol.md` — Sync copy.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/comparison-pipeline-analysis.md\n...\n    17\t\n    18\t### IC Advocate Position\n    19\tThe IronClaude pipeline analysis subsystem provides **programmatic, pre-execution analysis** of pipeline specifications: FMEA dual-signal failure mode classification, invariant registry, guard analysis, and dataflow tracing. These analytical passes detect implicit contracts between deliverables before they become runtime failures — operating on specifications, not post-failure artifacts. The 4-stage diagnostic chain (`run_diagnostic_chain()`) provides post-failure analysis with graceful per-stage degradation. Critically, both the analytical passes and the diagnostic chain are **pure Python** — deterministic, testable, and independent of LLM non-determinism.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.0_fidelity-refactor_/wiring-verification-gate-v1.0-release-spec.md\n...\n    47\t\n    48\t- No-op fallback detection (deferred to v1.1 pending shadow-mode data)\n    49\t- Cross-language analysis (Python only)\n    50\t- Runtime behavioral verification (see Smoke Test Gate proposal)\n    51\t- Dynamic dispatch resolution (`**kwargs`, `getattr`, `importlib`)\n    52\t- Modifying the `SemanticCheck` interface (no `pre_checks` in this release)\n    53\t\n    54\t---\n    55\t\n    56\t## 3. Architecture\n    57\t\n    58\t### 3.1 System Context\n    59\t\n    60\t```\n    61\tExisting Pipeline Infrastructure          New Component\n    62\t================================          =============\n    63\t\n    64\tpipeline/models.py                        audit/wiring_gate.py\n    65\t  GateCriteria ─────────────────────────>   WIRING_GATE (constant)\n    66\t  SemanticCheck ────────────────────────>   check functions\n    67\t\n    68\tpipeline/gates.py\n    69\t  gate_passed() ────────────────────────>   evaluates WIRING_GATE\n...\n   552\t\n   553\tif config.wiring_gate_mode == \"shadow\":\n   554\t    # Log result but do not affect task status\n   555\t    logger.info(f\"[shadow] Wiring gate: {report.total_findings} findings\")\n   556\telif config.wiring_gate_mode == \"soft\":\n   557\t    # Warn in TUI but do not block\n   558\t    if not report.passed:\n   559\t        tui.warn(f\"Wiring gate: {report.total_findings} findings\")\n   560\telif config.wiring_gate_mode == \"full\":\n   561\t    # Block task completion\n   562\t    passed, reason = gate_passed(wiring_report_path, WIRING_GATE)\n   563\t    if not passed:\n   564\t        # Trigger remediation via SprintGatePolicy\n   565\t        ...\n   566\t```\n...\n   735\t\n   736\t- Wiring analysis runs after every task in sprint execution\n   737\t- Results logged to `.sprint-state/wiring/` directory\n   738\t- No impact on task status or pipeline flow\n   739\t- Collect baseline: false positive rate, finding distribution, analysis time\n   740\t\n   741\t### Phase 2: Soft (release +1, pending shadow data review)\n   742\t\n   743\t- Findings surfaced as warnings in sprint TUI\n   744\t- Findings recorded in `DeferredRemediationLog`\n   745\t- Block only at release scope (per `resolve_gate_mode()` which returns BLOCKING for release)\n   746\t- Override available via `--skip-wiring-gate` flag\n   747\t\n   748\t**Threshold calibration for known FPR sources**:\n   749\t\n   750\tWhen setting Phase 2 activation thresholds from Phase 1 baseline data,\n   751\texplicitly account for the following known false-positive sources:\n   752\t\n   753\t| Source | Expected FPR contribution | v1.0 mitigation | Planned fix |\n   754\t|---|---|---|---|\n   755\t| Re-exported classes (import aliases) | 30–70% of unwired-callable findings | Raise Phase 2 unwired-callable threshold; document noise floor | v1.1 alias pre-pass |\n   756\t| `provider_dir_names` misconfiguration | 100% of orphan-module findings (silent) | Pre-activation validation checklist (Section 8 Phase 1) | N/A — config |\n   757\t\n   758\t**Decision rule**: Phase 2 MUST NOT be activated if Phase 1 unwired-callable\n   759\tFPR cannot be separated from the re-export noise floor. Document the estimated\n   760\tnoise floor in the Phase 1 report. Set Phase 2 thresholds at\n   761\t`measured_FPR + 2σ` above the noise floor estimate, not above zero.\n   762\t\n   763\t### Phase 3: Full (release +2, pending soft data review)\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/anti-instincts-gate-unified.md\n...\n   947\t\n   948\t### Enforcement Strategy\n   949\t\n   950\t<!-- Source: V1-C (spec structural audit), adapted per refactor-plan -->\n   951\t\n   952\tPhase 1 (immediate): Warning-only. The executor logs a warning if the ratio falls below 0.5 but does not block the pipeline. This allows shadow-mode validation on real specs before enforcement.\n   953\t\n   954\tPhase 2 (after validation): STRICT enforcement. If the structural count suggests the extraction is missing significant content, the executor re-triggers extraction or halts with an actionable error.\n   955\t\n   956\t---\n   957\t\n   958\t## 8. Gate Definition\n   959\t\n   960\t<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n   961\t\n   962\t### New Gate: `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE`\n   963\t\n   964\t**File**: `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py` (modify existing)\n   965\t\n   966\t```python\n   967\t# --- Anti-Instinct Gate check functions ---\n...\n   999\t\n  1000\t\n  1001\tdef _fingerprint_coverage_check(content: str) -> bool:\n  1002\t    \"\"\"Verify spec code-level identifiers have sufficient roadmap coverage.\n  1003\t\n  1004\t    This check requires both spec and roadmap content. Since semantic\n  1005\t    checks receive only a single content string, the real enforcement\n  1006\t    happens in the executor. This validates the executor's written result.\n  1007\t    \"\"\"\n  1008\t    fm = _parse_frontmatter(content)\n  1009\t    if fm is None:\n  1010\t        return False\n  1011\t    try:\n  1012\t        return float(fm.get(\"fingerprint_coverage\", 0.0)) >= 0.7\n  1013\t    except (ValueError, TypeError):\n  1014\t        return False\n  1015\t\n  1016\t\n  1017\t# --- Gate definition ---\n  1018\t\n  1019\tANTI_INSTINCT_GATE = GateCriteria(\n  1020\t    required_frontmatter_fields=[\n  1021\t        \"undischarged_obligations\",    # V2-A: integer count\n  1022\t        \"uncovered_contracts\",         # V5-1: integer count\n  1023\t        \"fingerprint_coverage\",        # V4-2: float 0.0-1.0\n  1024\t    ],\n  1025\t    min_lines=10,\n  1026\t    enforcement_tier=\"STRICT\",\n  1027\t    semantic_checks=[\n  1028\t        SemanticCheck(\n  1029\t            name=\"no_undischarged_obligations\",\n  1030\t            check_fn=_no_undischarged_obligations,\n  1031\t            failure_message=(\n  1032\t                \"Undischarged scaffolding obligations detected: early-phase \"\n  1033\t                \"mocks/stubs/skeletons have no corresponding replace/integrate/\"\n  1034\t                \"wire task in later phases\"\n  1035\t            ),\n  1036\t        ),\n  1037\t        SemanticCheck(\n  1038\t            name=\"integration_contracts_covered\",\n  1039\t            check_fn=_integration_contracts_covered,\n  1040\t            failure_message=(\n  1041\t                \"Spec integration contracts missing from roadmap: dispatch tables, \"\n  1042\t                \"registries, or injection points defined in spec have no explicit \"\n  1043\t                \"wiring task in roadmap\"\n  1044\t            ),\n  1045\t        ),\n...\n  1395\t\n  1396\t| File | Changes | Source |\n  1397\t|---|---|---|\n  1398\t| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py` | Add `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE` definition with 3 semantic checks; add 3 check functions (`_no_undischarged_obligations`, `_integration_contracts_covered`, `_fingerprint_coverage_check`); update `ALL_GATES` list to insert `(\"anti-instinct\", ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE)` between `merge` and `test-strategy` | V2-A + V5-1 + V4-2 |\n  1399\t| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` | Add anti-instinct step to `_build_steps()`; add structural audit hook after extract (`_run_structural_audit`); add `_run_anti_instinct_audit()` function; add import for `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE`; update `_get_all_step_ids()` to include `\"anti-instinct\"` | All |\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1-release-spec.md\n...\n    16\t\n    17\t### 0.3 Citation rule used\n    18\tCritical claims cite source file + section label. If section labels are absent, file heading context is used.\n    19\t\n    20\t---\n    21\t\n    22\t## 1. Release Scope and Goals\n    23\t\n    24\t### 1.1 Scope\n    25\tImplement a unified audit-gating capability that blocks completion/release transitions unless the corresponding gate passes at three scopes:\n    26\t1. Task gate\n    27\t2. Milestone gate\n    28\t3. Release gate\n    29\t\n    30\t(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Goal; Task-Level Gate; Milestone-Level Gate; Release-Level Gate)\n    31\t\n    32\t### 1.2 Primary goals\n    33\t1. Deterministic pass/fail gating with evidence-backed outputs\n    34\t2. Explicit audit workflow states for all scopes\n    35\t3. Single primary user interface (`/sc:audit-gate`)\n    36\t4. Rollout-safe enforcement (shadow → soft → full)\n    37\t\n    38\t(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Locked Decisions, Non-Functional Requirements, Command & Enforcement; `02-design-spec-v1.md` → Command/API Surface, Migration/Rollout; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → v1.1 Delta Summary)\n    39\t\n    40\t### 1.3 Out-of-scope for v1.2.1\n    41\t- New non-gating product features unrelated to transition control\n    42\t- Security hardening expansions not required for correctness of gate transitions\n    43\t- Full auto-tuning of profiles during rollout (deferred)\n    44\t\n    45\t(Constraint source: user hard requirement + `executive-summary.md` → deferred improvements)\n    46\t\n    47\t---\n    48\t\n    49\t## 2. Locked Decisions, Non-Goals, and Contradiction Resolution\n...\n   180\t\n   181\t(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Reporting + Non-Functional Requirements; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → GateResult schema)\n   182\t\n   183\t---\n   184\t\n   185\t## 6. Data Contracts and Versioning\n   186\t\n   187\t### 6.1 GateResult (normative v1.2.1)\n   188\tRequired fields:\n   189\t- `version`\n   190\t- `gate_run_id`\n   191\t- `scope`, `entity_id`, `profile`\n   192\t- `status`, `score`, `threshold`\n   193\t- `checks[]` (includes severity + evidence)\n   194\t- `drift_summary` (`edited`, `non_edited`)\n   195\t- `override` block\n   196\t- `timing` block\n   197\t- `artifacts` block\n   198\t- `failure_class` (v1.2 addition)\n   199\t\n   200\t(Source: `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → Canonical GateResult; `design-delta-v1.2.md` → Add 2)\n...\n   418\t\n   419\t## Top 5 Immediate Actions\n   420\t1. Finalize and sign off profile thresholds + major-severity behavior.\n   421\t2. Finalize retry/backoff/timeout and stale-state budgets.\n   422\t3. Ratify explicit legal/il"}]}]},"uuid":"9e2597cb-604c-419d-a351-95e0725eef36","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:47:38.262Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"82469001-31c6-4856-9466-0588008da443","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
